import numpy as np
cols=['AGE', 'GENDER', 'RACE', 'DRIVING_EXPERIENCE', 'EDUCATION', 'INCOME','VEHICLE_OWNERSHIP', 'VEHICLE_YEAR', 'MARRIED',
       'CHILDREN', 'VEHICLE_TYPE']
df1=df[df["OUTCOME"]==1]

for col in cols: 
        df2=pd.DataFrame(df1[col].value_counts(normalize=True))
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = ( 5 , 3 )) 
        sns.barplot(ax=ax,data=df2, x= df2.index, y= col)
         # Set label for x-axis 
        ax.set_xlabel( col , size = 12 ) 
         # Set label for y-axis 
        ax.set_ylabel( "Percentage of Claim" , size = 12 ) 
        # Set title for plot 
        ax.set_title( "Claim vs "+col , size = 12 ) 
  
        plt.show()

If we compare the percentage of claims made by different categorical groups, we can see that AGE, RACE, DRIVING_EXPERIENCE, EDUCATION, INCOME, VEHICLE_YEAR, MARRIED and VEHICLE_TYPE have significant effects on claiming the insurance.

Checking the missing mechanism¶

Types of missing data A classification of missing data was established by Little & Rubin in 1987 diving missing data into three categories:

a) MCAR : Missing completely at random b) MAR: Missing at random c) MNAR: Missing not at random In order to understand the difference between the differnet types of missig data, we will try to construct them ourserlves.

from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report

## Dividing Predictors and Response 
X, y = completed_dataset.iloc[:,:-1], completed_dataset.iloc[:,-1]
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test= train_test_split(X, y,
test_size=0.2, random_state=123)

Predictive model for OUTCOME¶

Here we are using XGBOOST to find a predictive model for the OUTCOME

In [67]:
import xgboost as xgb
#Creating an XGBoost classifier
model = xgb.XGBClassifier(tree_method="hist", enable_categorical=True, device="cuda")
#Training the model on the training data
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

#Making predictions on the test set
predictions = model.predict(X_test)

#Calculating accuracy
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, predictions)

print("Accuracy:", accuracy)
print("\nClassification Report:")
print(classification_report(y_test, predictions))

## ROC AUC Curve
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score

# predict probabilities
probs = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]
# calculate scores
auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, probs)
print('XGBOOST: ROC AUC=%.3f' % (auc))
# calculate roc curves
fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, probs)
# plot the roc curve for the model
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, marker='.')
# axis labels
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
# show the legend
#plt.legend()
# show the plot
plt.show()
